[SPEAKER_00]: our specific line item budget priorities so much as the overall atmosphere in which the budget is created, the atmosphere in which we discuss the budget, how much information we have about or maybe perhaps the disproportionate emphasis on year-by-year budgets as opposed to an actual plan for how we're going to achieve our goals over time.

170
00:17:49,383 --> 00:18:02,319
[SPEAKER_00]: Councilor Scarpelli mentioned that we are, we often feel in the dark about how much we have to spend on what and how our priority and how our priorities are going to actually be made manifest in the community.

171
00:18:05,302 --> 00:18:11,283
[SPEAKER_00]: I think that we have a mismatch between data and quality information, because some of this data is out there.

172
00:18:11,323 --> 00:18:13,984
[SPEAKER_00]: We saw a draft of a capital improvement plan.

173
00:18:14,004 --> 00:18:15,344
[SPEAKER_00]: We got a presentation on that.

174
00:18:15,384 --> 00:18:18,105
[SPEAKER_00]: We do occasionally get these big picture numbers.

175
00:18:18,145 --> 00:18:19,765
[SPEAKER_00]: We've asked for AP warrant articles.

176
00:18:19,805 --> 00:18:20,745
[SPEAKER_00]: We're starting to get them.

177
00:18:21,525 --> 00:18:24,086
[SPEAKER_00]: But not all data is equally useful.

178
00:18:24,106 --> 00:18:31,707
[SPEAKER_00]: I think if we know where to look, we can find the information on how much is in certain accounts, how much is available, from what sources.

179
00:18:33,268 --> 00:18:34,208
[SPEAKER_00]: But what we don't

180
00:18:34,909 --> 00:18:39,626
[SPEAKER_00]: No, I think what we're really all looking to know, trying to be desperate to know is,

181
00:18:41,815 --> 00:18:49,879
[SPEAKER_00]: how exactly are we going to get from right here, the FY 24 budget to any of our goals being accomplished?

182
00:18:49,919 --> 00:18:52,201
[SPEAKER_00]: How are we going to go from point A to point B?

183
00:18:52,221 --> 00:19:05,368
[SPEAKER_00]: How are we going to go from the departmental budget hearings that we're going to hear about the nitty gritty of this year and these staffing levels and this grant funding opportunity and all of the line item detail level work to how does that connect to

184
00:19:06,608 --> 00:19:12,430
[SPEAKER_00]: the things that our residents ask us about and the things that our residents see affecting their quality of life.

185
00:19:13,230 --> 00:19:31,416
[SPEAKER_00]: I think for me, my biggest budget priority really is getting to a place where we can start connecting those dots at least once a year during budget season to get out of this environment in which we have no idea

186
00:19:33,440 --> 00:19:35,061
[SPEAKER_00]: how much potential we're leaving on the table.

187
00:19:35,101 --> 00:19:39,505
[SPEAKER_00]: We have no idea why things are not being funded more adequately than they are.

188
00:19:39,545 --> 00:19:48,693
[SPEAKER_00]: We don't know exactly why the numbers are coming to us the way that they are and what other potential there is and what kind of long-term strategy they're connected to.

189
00:19:48,993 --> 00:20:00,663
[SPEAKER_00]: And to make that more concrete, I think that apart from a couple specific line item preferences, my biggest priority for this budget season is asking what exactly we're going to do with the free cash that is available to us this fiscal year.

190
00:20:02,424 --> 00:20:07,125
[SPEAKER_00]: We haven't seen, I haven't seen any official numbers yet, so I don't know what we're going to be looking at.

191
00:20:07,865 --> 00:20:17,947
[SPEAKER_00]: But we know last year it was a fight to get level funding, let alone level service for many of our very critical constituent services and departments.

192
00:20:18,067 --> 00:20:25,588
[SPEAKER_00]: And given how we were told, we have many, many, many millions of free cash that was certified last summer.

193
00:20:27,188 --> 00:20:30,249
[SPEAKER_00]: If it is a fight, again, to get level funding,

194
00:20:31,989 --> 00:20:35,611
[SPEAKER_00]: let alone level service for many of our departmentals, for many of our departments this year.

195
00:20:37,292 --> 00:20:38,072
[SPEAKER_00]: We have to know why.

196
00:20:38,092 --> 00:20:42,014
[SPEAKER_00]: I wanna know why there's money being left on the table.

197
00:20:42,794 --> 00:20:59,343
[SPEAKER_00]: And often I think we use that term to describe development opportunities that we're not pursuing as fast as we could be because we lack the staff to do so, but rather the resources that we actually have in a context when so many constituent needs are going unmet, how could we possibly

198
00:21:01,292 --> 00:21:08,439
[SPEAKER_00]: defend not marshaling those resources to connect directly to the constituent services that people already know that they're missing, because we hear about it all the time.

199
00:21:11,522 --> 00:21:21,431
[SPEAKER_00]: In terms of specific priorities that I hope to see from the administration in the coming weeks, we did manage to get

200
00:21:23,185 --> 00:21:33,067
[SPEAKER_00]: that guarantee from the administration last year that we get $50,000 earmarked for a legal consultant for zoning recodification work, which I am really grateful to the administration for.

201
00:21:33,107 --> 00:21:39,269
[SPEAKER_00]: We weren't able to act on that this past fiscal year, so I'd like to see that maintained because we're almost ready to start acting upon it.

202
00:21:39,309 --> 00:21:41,489
[SPEAKER_00]: That's probably my number one priority.

203
00:21:46,674 --> 00:22:09,693
[SPEAKER_00]: The only other specifics that felt relevant for me to bring up in this meeting, given where we are in this austerity environment and knowing how low the ceiling is in what we're likely to be able to fund, is being able to meet the requested budget number promulgated by the school committee, being able to maintain level service for the public library budget.

204
00:22:12,521 --> 00:22:19,086
[SPEAKER_00]: Because of this austerity environment that we've been in for such a long time, you know, all of those things that I mentioned really should be non-negotiables.

205
00:22:19,286 --> 00:22:26,871
[SPEAKER_00]: It's a little, it strikes me as a little surreal to have to mention those as budget priorities when those should be, when those should go without saying.

206
00:22:28,773 --> 00:22:33,696
[SPEAKER_00]: But given the budget conversation that we had this time last year and how we really did have to fight for level funding for

207
00:22:34,810 --> 00:22:47,678
[SPEAKER_00]: well, I mean, we had to advocate for level funding regardless of how it actually ended up for those extremely essential government services that, as Councillor Scarpelli mentioned, do target some of our most vulnerable members of our community.

208
00:22:49,740 --> 00:22:54,603
[SPEAKER_00]: It's hard to call that a wish list when these are things that should never have to fear going underfunded.

209
00:22:59,413 --> 00:23:14,908
[SPEAKER_00]: So just to end on, you know, again, the sort of the longitudinal note, I think what's what's most frustrating to me is that we have these disparate data points, we have these disparate plans, what we don't have is any sort of overarching narrative for how

210
00:23:15,518 --> 00:23:27,686
[SPEAKER_00]: individual data points, individual plans, individual staff, people, individual annual budgets coalesce to any sort of forecasting for when we are going to achieve our goals to what extent.

211
00:23:28,067 --> 00:23:33,370
[SPEAKER_00]: And I think that's where the budget director role could come in and other roles similar to that.

212
00:23:33,410 --> 00:23:34,291
[SPEAKER_00]: You know, I wish we had

213
00:23:35,772 --> 00:23:46,435
[SPEAKER_00]: you know, a cohort, I think we could use a cohort of project managers dispersed across, you know, this whole city government, we have people working individually doing incredible work with the resources that they have in various departments.

214
00:23:47,616 --> 00:23:57,458
[SPEAKER_00]: I'm often, you know, just absolutely blown away by how effective our department has our city staff are able to be under really very understaffed and austere conditions.

215
00:23:59,819 --> 00:24:02,700
[SPEAKER_00]: But we're already so behind on so many of our stated

216
00:24:03,277 --> 00:24:04,519
[SPEAKER_00]: shared goals for the city.

217
00:24:06,221 --> 00:24:07,583
[SPEAKER_00]: We need to start laying that foundation.

218
00:24:08,685 --> 00:24:14,129
[SPEAKER_00]: with our financial planning, with our project managing, with our project planning that goes beyond one year at a time.

219
00:24:16,391 --> 00:24:25,377
[SPEAKER_00]: If we just continue on this path of doing as much as we can with as much as we're given on a year-to-year basis, that's how we've been going for the past several decades.

220
00:24:25,958 --> 00:24:36,085
[SPEAKER_00]: And I think we can all look around and see how behind that leaves us feeling on our infrastructure, on our staff development, and just on the quality of life that residents feel that they have.

221
00:24:36,726 --> 00:24:36,926
[SPEAKER_00]: Thank you.

222
00:24:38,166 --> 00:24:40,347
[SPEAKER_07]: Thank you, Councilor Collins, Councilor Sang and Councilor Carvillo.

223
00:24:41,367 --> 00:24:42,768
[SPEAKER_01]: Thank you, President Morrell.

224
00:24:43,368 --> 00:24:51,692
[SPEAKER_01]: I think my fellow councilors have have touched on the amount of information that we know as a council right now.

225
00:24:54,158 --> 00:25:01,769
[SPEAKER_01]: I, I was stuck in traffic so I didn't catch cancer bears his statements but I, I assume he's also touched on that as well.

226
00:25:02,590 --> 00:25:08,718
[SPEAKER_01]: Um, when I think about a budget, I think of it as a statement of governance values and signaling.

227
00:25:10,040 --> 00:25:10,120
[SPEAKER_01]: that.

228
00:25:10,160 --> 00:25:29,469
[SPEAKER_01]: Um when I was thinking about how to create this list, um, some of the items that I put on there are clear needs that we have as it as a city that, um, residents have been reaching out to us about, um and some of them are loftier goals that you know if we wanted to do 100% of that project, we most likely couldn't afford it.

229
00:25:30,210 --> 00:25:31,930
[SPEAKER_01]: Um but it would be helpful to

230
00:25:40,194 --> 00:26:02,524
[SPEAKER_01]: I believe that this is a good time to bring it up to administration to say, look, we would like something in the budget about this, even if we can't get something in the budget about this, we want to see a plan moving forward on these goals, so that in the future for fiscal 25 and 26, and future budgets, we know that something is going to be done on it.

231
00:26:04,345 --> 00:26:05,966
[SPEAKER_01]: know that we have the full picture.

232
00:26:05,986 --> 00:26:07,186
[SPEAKER_01]: Even though we don't have the full picture.

233
00:26:07,206 --> 00:26:08,087
[SPEAKER_01]: We know some facts.

234
00:26:08,107 --> 00:26:11,428
[SPEAKER_01]: Um we know that our needs exceed the funding.

235
00:26:11,829 --> 00:26:16,191
[SPEAKER_01]: Um most likely exceed the funding that we have now in revenue as a city.

236
00:26:16,211 --> 00:26:18,932
[SPEAKER_01]: Um and that's not to talk about a wish list.

237
00:26:18,992 --> 00:26:22,734
[SPEAKER_01]: It's to talk about what department heads feel our needs for the city.

238
00:26:22,754 --> 00:26:25,135
[SPEAKER_01]: What residents keep reaching us out to us about

239
00:26:31,358 --> 00:26:32,359
[SPEAKER_01]: should be quite significant.

240
00:26:32,399 --> 00:26:40,887
[SPEAKER_01]: I mean, it's not a matter of one or two money papers that come across us once a month throughout council meetings.

241
00:26:41,527 --> 00:26:42,488
[SPEAKER_01]: It's a big picture.

242
00:26:42,608 --> 00:26:48,674
[SPEAKER_01]: We need to sit down during budget season and talk about overall how are we going to meet these needs.

243
00:26:48,974 --> 00:26:50,655
[SPEAKER_01]: It's not about rejecting one paper.

244
00:26:52,257 --> 00:26:56,641
[SPEAKER_01]: We have a wish list on top of that, on top of those needs.

245
00:26:58,262 --> 00:26:59,283
[SPEAKER_01]: And that wish list.

246
00:26:59,924 --> 00:27:06,231
[SPEAKER_01]: You know, I think Councillor Collins is right we shouldn't call it a wish list, it's really just an extended version of our needs.

247
00:27:09,159 --> 00:27:16,921
[SPEAKER_01]: us, it's the equivalent of us going up to a department head and saying, Look, if we had unlimited money, what do you need to thrive in your department?

248
00:27:16,961 --> 00:27:18,722
[SPEAKER_01]: What do you need to succeed in City Hall?

249
00:27:19,822 --> 00:27:20,983
[SPEAKER_01]: And so it's not really a wish list.

250
00:27:21,003 --> 00:27:25,184
[SPEAKER_01]: It's, you know, it's just like an extension of that list of needs.

251
00:27:25,824 --> 00:27:32,026
[SPEAKER_01]: And we know that we have this conflict in the city between one time and recurring needs of spending.

252
00:27:32,046 --> 00:27:32,106
[SPEAKER_01]: And

253
00:27:35,187 --> 00:27:41,308
[SPEAKER_01]: I think one example of that is what we might see in the future with Esther funding and with in teaching positions.

254
00:27:42,249 --> 00:27:55,972
[SPEAKER_01]: We'll need to talk about how, how are we taking, how are we approaching this $25 million in free cash, how are we approaching the bigger, bigger question of revenue in the city, and how are what how are we sorting out

255
00:27:56,592 --> 00:28:03,781
[SPEAKER_01]: what positions are going to go away what positions we're going to keep and if we want to keep positions that are slated are scheduled to go away.

256
00:28:04,301 --> 00:28:08,767
[SPEAKER_01]: How do we fund those positions and I think that highlights.

257
00:28:10,595 --> 00:28:20,998
[SPEAKER_01]: I think a strategy that we should take on as a, as a council on this budget season which is the number one pushing for a long term vision, and even if we're focusing on the fiscal 24 budget this year.

258
00:28:21,018 --> 00:28:33,502
[SPEAKER_01]: I think we need to take this month and ask about larger plans for bringing in new growth and new revenue for future fiscal years as well, because I think Councilor carabino says this all the time.

259
00:28:33,522 --> 00:28:37,163
[SPEAKER_01]: You know, it takes a while for the shovel shovel to get in the ground as well.

260
00:28:37,923 --> 00:28:40,425
[SPEAKER_01]: And so I think it's important for us to talk about that.

261
00:28:40,745 --> 00:28:53,352
[SPEAKER_01]: I think, um, I think Councillor Collins brought it up, and I would support this, um, maintaining funding for zoning consulting team I think is very much top of the priority list in that regard.

262
00:28:54,572 --> 00:29:01,216
[SPEAKER_01]: Strategically, we need to look at ways that we can bring in more money and invest in smart development.

263
00:29:01,776 --> 00:29:09,800
[SPEAKER_01]: and in city staff that would focus on expanding our commercial revenue base and revitalizing our businesses.

264
00:29:12,593 --> 00:29:18,796
[SPEAKER_01]: I think in talking with OPDS, we have made a lot of strides as a city when it comes to these things.

265
00:29:19,217 --> 00:29:25,400
[SPEAKER_01]: But the thing is, now we have staff that we need to, vacancies that we need to fill in those offices.

266
00:29:26,360 --> 00:29:39,968
[SPEAKER_01]: They need more funding and support from the city budget in terms of reaching out to businesses to teach them smarter business strategies and to help them with blight and infrastructure.

267
00:29:41,029 --> 00:29:44,792
[SPEAKER_01]: It is helpful for us to have outside feedback and consultant reports.

268
00:29:44,852 --> 00:29:54,981
[SPEAKER_01]: And I'm not saying that we turn to consultants all the time, but oftentimes on sensitive issues, those reports do help us have a better sense of how to target our spending.

269
00:29:56,042 --> 00:29:57,843
[SPEAKER_01]: And so I did want to put that out there.

270
00:29:58,824 --> 00:30:00,526
[SPEAKER_01]: Getting on to my shortlist.

271
00:30:02,387 --> 00:30:05,408
[SPEAKER_01]: I think all of us here are fully supportive of the Medford Public Schools.

272
00:30:05,448 --> 00:30:08,068
[SPEAKER_01]: I think we've heard a lot from parents of the Medford Public Schools.

273
00:30:08,608 --> 00:30:15,590
[SPEAKER_01]: I did put out a survey to residents in the last week, which got around 125 responses.

274
00:30:16,990 --> 00:30:24,752
[SPEAKER_01]: And about half of respondents mentioned that the biggest problem facing Medford is lack of funding for our schools.

275
00:30:25,973 --> 00:30:30,734
[SPEAKER_01]: And going hand in hand with education is fully funding our library system as well.

276
00:30:33,155 --> 00:30:49,513
[SPEAKER_01]: A lot of residents unexpectedly, very unexpectedly, very unsurprisingly pointed to the state of our roads, sidewalks, and bike lanes as a major issue here in Medford as well, and so I think about a third of respondents mentioned those.

277
00:30:50,174 --> 00:30:51,656
[SPEAKER_01]: are more than a third actually.

278
00:30:51,676 --> 00:31:04,453
[SPEAKER_01]: I mean, so I would like to see something in this budget that commits to reducing that road and sidewalk repair backlog and look, I mean, wish list, but I think it's important to make that point in this council.

279
00:31:06,940 --> 00:31:25,168
[SPEAKER_01]: This is a big issue that's been popping up a lot in our community that I think Councilor Carrillo has put forward some suggestions for that I've been working with school committee members and, and other parents in the away from the council chambers is the need for more after school programming.

280
00:31:26,553 --> 00:31:54,259
[SPEAKER_01]: It's a more difficult problem than just throwing money at it, but we need some signaling from the administration that we're going to commit to either putting more money towards hiring more staff for existing programming and increasing capacity there, or some planning for future facilities or future programs as well.

281
00:31:55,614 --> 00:32:01,358
[SPEAKER_01]: Um, and these last two things are more wish list items that I don't think, um.

282
00:32:02,419 --> 00:32:11,384
[SPEAKER_01]: That that I think are important to bring up while we have city staff before us, but I understand are more reaches, um, putting, um.

283
00:32:12,425 --> 00:32:14,086
[SPEAKER_01]: Putting money towards a grant writer.

284
00:32:14,106 --> 00:32:20,170
[SPEAKER_01]: A great manager would I think would really help us, um, capture more revenue or more.

285
00:32:20,270 --> 00:32:20,570
[SPEAKER_01]: It's not

286
00:32:26,705 --> 00:32:32,649
[SPEAKER_01]: It's sad to say it, but much of our city departments depend on grants to survive.

287
00:32:33,829 --> 00:32:41,374
[SPEAKER_01]: And it's not a sustainable long-term strategy, but in the short term, I think that's something that would net us more money than we spend.

288
00:32:42,054 --> 00:32:45,857
[SPEAKER_01]: And I've been fielding a lot of calls about rodents in Medford.

289
00:32:46,377 --> 00:32:53,401
[SPEAKER_01]: And so a lot of residents want us to put some more money towards a more robust rodent mitigation strategy.

290
00:32:53,461 --> 00:32:54,502
[SPEAKER_01]: And they understand that we can't

291
00:32:54,962 --> 00:33:02,648
[SPEAKER_01]: eliminate all rodents in our city, but a little bit of looking at what other cities around us are doing.

292
00:33:02,668 --> 00:33:08,011
[SPEAKER_01]: I think people look at other cities and wonder why Medford's not even trying.

293
00:33:08,331 --> 00:33:11,133
[SPEAKER_01]: And so we need to signal that we are trying.

294
00:33:12,154 --> 00:33:12,434
[SPEAKER_01]: Thank you.

295
00:33:13,055 --> 00:33:13,775
[SPEAKER_07]: Thank you, Councilor Seng.

296
00:33:13,935 --> 00:33:14,616
[SPEAKER_07]: Councilor Carvio.

297
00:33:15,737 --> 00:33:16,577
[SPEAKER_04]: Thank you, Madam President.

298
00:33:17,178 --> 00:33:17,798
[SPEAKER_04]: So here we are.

299
00:33:18,999 --> 00:33:19,880
[SPEAKER_04]: It's May 23rd.

300
00:33:20,060 --> 00:33:23,082
[SPEAKER_04]: We're five weeks away from our budget.

301
00:33:24,270 --> 00:33:26,771
[SPEAKER_04]: uh, date that we have to have, we have to pass the budget.

302
00:33:26,791 --> 00:33:32,133
[SPEAKER_04]: I haven't seen anything, haven't talked to anybody, no idea what the budget was.

303
00:33:32,413 --> 00:33:38,915
[SPEAKER_04]: But you know, you want to think that, um, that frustrates me one of the most, I mean, so that we all have good ideas where we should have our money.

304
00:33:38,935 --> 00:33:46,038
[SPEAKER_04]: But in the last two to three years, other cities have been flush with cash.

305
00:33:47,258 --> 00:33:51,040
[SPEAKER_04]: We've gotten millions and millions of dollars of state and federal money.

306
00:33:52,054 --> 00:33:54,776
[SPEAKER_04]: that you've seen other cities take advantage.

307
00:33:55,637 --> 00:34:00,721
[SPEAKER_04]: Where did all our money go that we got from the federal government and from the state during these last three years?

308
00:34:00,741 --> 00:34:02,122
[SPEAKER_04]: This money's gone now.

309
00:34:02,783 --> 00:34:03,964
[SPEAKER_04]: This is the last year for the money.

310
00:34:04,704 --> 00:34:11,190
[SPEAKER_04]: And I say, the schools, all these programs that we've been depending on these programs, these programs are all drying up now.

311
00:34:11,210 --> 00:34:12,170
[SPEAKER_04]: They're coming to an end.

312
00:34:12,571 --> 00:34:18,656
[SPEAKER_04]: We'll probably squeak through this year's budget with virtually no growth.

313
00:34:19,867 --> 00:34:29,135
[SPEAKER_04]: The big problem is going to be this next year, because we're not going to have all this state and federal money that was thrown around the last couple of years.

314
00:34:29,555 --> 00:34:29,935
[SPEAKER_04]: It's gone.

315
00:34:30,236 --> 00:34:31,396
[SPEAKER_04]: The school's not going to have the money.

316
00:34:31,416 --> 00:34:32,237
[SPEAKER_04]: It's gone.

317
00:34:32,718 --> 00:34:34,139
[SPEAKER_04]: How long can the city live on grants?

318
00:34:34,259 --> 00:34:36,401
[SPEAKER_04]: It's a causal segment.

319
00:34:36,541 --> 00:34:41,325
[SPEAKER_04]: Their grants are great, and they're nice to have, but that's not how we operate.

320
00:34:41,765 --> 00:34:43,687
[SPEAKER_04]: We operate with money.

321
00:34:44,067 --> 00:34:47,490
[SPEAKER_04]: We're talking about our zoning consultants.

322
00:34:48,605 --> 00:34:51,067
[SPEAKER_04]: Well, it's a year now it's gone.

323
00:34:51,387 --> 00:34:53,028
[SPEAKER_04]: It's a year we haven't seen the zoning consultant.

324
00:34:53,869 --> 00:35:00,874
[SPEAKER_04]: So the building boom is gonna be passing us by.

325
00:35:00,894 --> 00:35:07,699
[SPEAKER_04]: So I mean, there's no rush with the zoning consultant now because everyone, all the buildings, everybody's built around this.

326
00:35:07,739 --> 00:35:15,424
[SPEAKER_04]: And even though we're the last bastion of business to go, we have no plan.

327
00:35:17,218 --> 00:35:22,400
[SPEAKER_04]: And this council worked diligently for two years to do the codification.

328
00:35:22,860 --> 00:35:26,161
[SPEAKER_04]: We should have went right into the zoning almost immediately.

329
00:35:26,821 --> 00:35:29,002
[SPEAKER_04]: So we would have been ahead of the game.

330
00:35:30,023 --> 00:35:34,424
[SPEAKER_04]: By the time we go through the RFP process, it's gonna be another 90 days.

331
00:35:37,005 --> 00:35:39,106
[SPEAKER_04]: And by the time, yeah, you say, where are we now?

332
00:35:39,386 --> 00:35:41,467
[SPEAKER_04]: We're gonna be toward the end of this year.

333
00:35:43,273 --> 00:35:46,295
[SPEAKER_04]: You know, that's just, it's utterly ridiculous.

334
00:35:46,836 --> 00:35:48,937
[SPEAKER_04]: You know, and we talked about the capital plan.

335
00:35:51,079 --> 00:35:55,242
[SPEAKER_04]: We all sat here and we listened to the capital plan, but Council of Mayors made the point.

336
00:35:57,443 --> 00:36:03,848
[SPEAKER_04]: Why aren't we taking stock of our capital issues that we have before we go looking at other things?

337
00:36:04,248 --> 00:36:07,510
[SPEAKER_04]: Let's fix our capital things that need fixing now.

338
00:36:08,591 --> 00:36:10,592
[SPEAKER_04]: We don't, okay, and those are gone.

339
00:36:10,832 --> 00:36:11,893
[SPEAKER_04]: We're still waiting for the legal.

340
00:36:14,355 --> 00:36:17,401
[SPEAKER_04]: I want what I asked for last year, and we haven't seen anything.

341
00:36:18,182 --> 00:36:26,776
[SPEAKER_04]: You have a library here that you own for about 60 cents on the dollar, 50 cents on the dollar, and we're struggling to fund that.

342
00:36:28,418 --> 00:36:35,166
[SPEAKER_04]: I mean, you know, this is not a, you know, as Councilor Scott said, you know, people think that we're sitting here beating up the mayor.

343
00:36:35,186 --> 00:36:36,087
[SPEAKER_04]: It's not beating up the mayor.

344
00:36:36,768 --> 00:36:40,553
[SPEAKER_04]: I mean, we're asking legitimate questions that should be asked.

345
00:36:40,593 --> 00:36:45,979
[SPEAKER_04]: And I say, we're going to squeak through this year's budget somehow with no growth and no anything happening.

346
00:36:47,175 --> 00:36:53,619
[SPEAKER_04]: Next year is gonna be the real test of this council and this budget, where we're gonna find the money that's disappeared.

347
00:36:54,459 --> 00:36:59,082
[SPEAKER_04]: And it's gone from the federal government and all these other plans.

348
00:36:59,843 --> 00:37:01,404
[SPEAKER_04]: It's gone, never to come back again.

349
00:37:01,424 --> 00:37:05,286
[SPEAKER_04]: And I don't think we use that money wisely.

350
00:37:05,666 --> 00:37:15,572
[SPEAKER_04]: And let's say, I think we've all seen all the surrounding cities, all flush with cash, and here we are, we're operating at a deficit, but meanwhile, we're sitting on $25 million.

351
00:37:17,909 --> 00:37:20,290
[SPEAKER_04]: Tell us what we should think here.

352
00:37:20,350 --> 00:37:22,010
[SPEAKER_04]: Again, this is not a beat up session.

353
00:37:22,470 --> 00:37:29,873
[SPEAKER_04]: It's just asking, you know, just questions that need to be asked.

354
00:37:31,013 --> 00:37:33,254
[SPEAKER_07]: Any further discussion from the counselors?

355
00:37:36,074 --> 00:37:39,075
[SPEAKER_07]: I mean, I would just know I agree with pretty much everything that's been said.

356
00:37:39,115 --> 00:37:43,957
[SPEAKER_07]: I think those big, you know, I agree with Councilor Scarpelli where there is no shortage of what we need.

357
00:37:45,077 --> 00:37:47,578
[SPEAKER_07]: We're not going to get a lot of those things, most of those things.

358
00:37:48,418 --> 00:38:02,668
[SPEAKER_07]: but I will definitely beat the drum to make sure we continue to get that money for the zoning consultant so that we fund the library that we are committed to, that it can operate on the level that it needs to, that to also continue to be certified, correct?

359
00:38:02,688 --> 00:38:11,633
[SPEAKER_07]: It needs to operate a certain way to continue to be certified by the state, as well as respond to the budget requests of our school committee that they believe to fully fund our schools.

360
00:38:13,315 --> 00:38:13,875
[SPEAKER_07]: I'm hopeful,

361
00:38:14,970 --> 00:38:20,153
[SPEAKER_07]: I will go into this hopeful that this year the mayor will hear our requests and entertain our requests.

362
00:38:20,693 --> 00:38:25,656
[SPEAKER_07]: I think what was most disappointing last year was it wasn't a, I heard your requests, here's why I can't meet them.

363
00:38:25,916 --> 00:38:28,177
[SPEAKER_07]: It was almost as if we never made the requests.

364
00:38:28,758 --> 00:38:31,559
[SPEAKER_07]: So I look forward to at least a dialogue.

365
00:38:31,699 --> 00:38:33,040
[SPEAKER_07]: I hope we can get much more than that.

366
00:38:35,021 --> 00:38:41,985
[SPEAKER_07]: If there's no further discussion from the council, I can open up if there's any members of the public who wish to speak at this time, either on Zoom or in person.

367
00:38:43,202 --> 00:38:47,288
[SPEAKER_07]: So either Will or anyone on Zoom.

368
00:38:47,308 --> 00:38:48,330
[SPEAKER_07]: Going back to vices and mayors.

369
00:38:49,051 --> 00:38:50,152
[SPEAKER_02]: I just want to say that, you know

370
00:38:51,920 --> 00:38:59,303
[SPEAKER_02]: It's a fun day when Councillor Scarpelli is going down the list of all the things we need and I'm, I'm the one with the measured minor request.

371
00:39:01,203 --> 00:39:06,625
[SPEAKER_02]: So, yeah, it's like we swapped records or something.

372
00:39:06,825 --> 00:39:13,008
[SPEAKER_02]: But I completely I just since I spoke first and then everyone else spoke I completely agree with what everybody said I think we all hit on.

373
00:39:13,808 --> 00:39:28,811
[SPEAKER_02]: different pieces of the issue, from small to large, from just keeping what we already have to finding a plan to fix all of those big, big needs that you listed, Councilor Scarabelli, and everyone else touched on.

374
00:39:28,871 --> 00:39:35,792
[SPEAKER_02]: But yeah, it's, what did you say, Councilor Caravaglio, we'll skate on by?

375
00:39:35,812 --> 00:39:39,332
[SPEAKER_04]: We'll skate by this year.

376
00:39:39,472 --> 00:39:40,132
[SPEAKER_04]: Yeah.

377
00:39:40,192 --> 00:39:42,813
[SPEAKER_04]: And we'll use up the last of the little bit of funds that we got left, but

378
00:39:43,732 --> 00:39:47,994
[SPEAKER_04]: next year is going to be the real test of where we are.

379
00:39:48,354 --> 00:39:48,634
[SPEAKER_02]: Yeah.

380
00:39:49,375 --> 00:39:50,235
[SPEAKER_02]: Yep.

381
00:39:50,635 --> 00:39:51,015
[SPEAKER_02]: Thank you.

382
00:39:51,276 --> 00:39:52,456
[SPEAKER_07]: Thank you, Councillor Collins.

383
00:39:52,516 --> 00:39:54,237
[SPEAKER_07]: And then we do have someone who would like to speak.

384
00:39:55,052 --> 00:40:17,025
[SPEAKER_00]: Thank you, President moral just just quickly I think and to vice president, there's this point it is, I know at least for myself it's a stark contrast between the laundry list that I came in with a year ago, and today, but just, you know, for the for any residents out there who are listening to our discussion and kind of feeling the absence of some, if there's any specifics that we failed to mention.

385
00:40:17,925 --> 00:40:20,727
[SPEAKER_00]: I think the counselors probably covered a lot of the ones that I have in the back of my mind.

386
00:40:21,267 --> 00:40:25,528
[SPEAKER_00]: you know, but for the residents thinking, well, why didn't you talk more about the need for afterschool?

387
00:40:25,568 --> 00:40:28,729
[SPEAKER_00]: Why didn't you talk about traffic calming measures?

388
00:40:28,769 --> 00:40:30,149
[SPEAKER_00]: Why didn't you talk about bike lanes?

389
00:40:30,189 --> 00:40:32,730
[SPEAKER_00]: Why didn't you talk about XYZ?

390
00:40:32,770 --> 00:40:37,711
[SPEAKER_00]: Because there's a lot of XYZs, you know, the kind of, I was searching for a metaphor when I was preparing for this meeting today.

391
00:40:37,751 --> 00:40:48,433
[SPEAKER_00]: And the, you know, the thing that came to mind for me was, you know, we have to build the boat before we can use the oars, you know, I think, or, or whatever version of that, you know, fill in the mantle of yourself.

392
00:40:48,513 --> 00:40:50,594
[SPEAKER_00]: But I think, especially given our

393
00:40:51,594 --> 00:40:51,814
[SPEAKER_00]: that.

394
00:40:51,854 --> 00:41:01,120
[SPEAKER_00]: Given the conversation that we had last year, which I think is, you know, hung very heavy over this year and forecasting into the next fiscal year when a lot of this grant funding just goes away.

395
00:41:01,140 --> 00:41:11,065
[SPEAKER_00]: Um it is painful for me to be very aware of all the needs going on met in the community and be aware of all the residents who are very aware of all the needs

396
00:41:16,888 --> 00:41:29,420
[SPEAKER_00]: But it needs to start with the big picture, it needs to start with the planning and needs to start with the capital planning and needs to start with the project planning and needs to start with getting more of our operating budget out of grants and into revenue that we can depend on and figuring out where that revenue comes from.

397
00:41:32,475 --> 00:41:49,747
[SPEAKER_00]: figuring out how to fund the gears that make the whole machine run so that we can eventually have that trickle down into the many, many slices of constituent services, particularly for our underrepresented constituents that we're not currently able to fulfill, to our shame.

398
00:41:50,367 --> 00:41:50,587
[SPEAKER_00]: Thank you.

399
00:41:52,008 --> 00:42:06,015
[SPEAKER_01]: I'll be brief because I know someone's waiting but um, I think we made this point last year, and I've really been drumming on about it, we have some great plans as a city we have good teachers good people working for us in the city.

400
00:42:06,975 --> 00:42:20,522
[SPEAKER_01]: I've passed on the bunch of our studies and plans to experts in the climate field and different, different fields and they think that the plans are better than the states, and better than other cities.

401
00:42:21,382 --> 00:42:28,125
[SPEAKER_01]: But the thing is, none of these plans will be implemented unless we have that conversation about how we're going to fund those plans.

402
00:42:29,345 --> 00:42:40,790
[SPEAKER_01]: And so I think we've all talked about how much of a black box it can feel working on the budget and how difficult it is to put forward recommendations without knowing the full picture.

403
00:42:42,210 --> 00:42:58,474
[SPEAKER_01]: I think there's tons of small ideas I would love our city to do, but without an idea of what our staff capacity is, it's hard to put that on a list today and hard to talk about it without directly asking administration about it.

404
00:42:59,454 --> 00:43:08,976
[SPEAKER_01]: Even though we face all those challenges, I think it's important to highlight the need to push for those big picture ideas as well.

405
00:43:09,577 --> 00:43:10,257
[SPEAKER_07]: Thank you, Councilor Seng.

406
00:43:10,277 --> 00:43:11,117
[SPEAKER_07]: Yeah, I would agree that we have

407
00:43:11,642 --> 00:43:19,765
[SPEAKER_07]: many, many wonderful city employees and school employees that know how to do more with less and wouldn't it be nice if it didn't have to be that way.

408
00:43:20,025 --> 00:43:26,067
[SPEAKER_07]: So we'll get, hopefully we get that boat first before we get the, hopefully we'll get that boat.

