00:43:36,557 --> 00:43:38,578
[SPEAKER_03]: Hi, Jen Sullivan, Marston Street.

416
00:43:40,260 --> 00:43:59,032
[SPEAKER_03]: I wanted to know, is there anything that we as sort of involved residents can do to, there's a lot of us that are invested in what happens here, and we don't want to watch another circus, and that's from everyone.

417
00:43:59,512 --> 00:44:03,315
[SPEAKER_03]: And what can we do to sort of support

418
00:44:04,214 --> 00:44:11,897
[SPEAKER_03]: better transparency and communication and not meet it with anger and try to really get some progress.

419
00:44:12,897 --> 00:44:23,661
[SPEAKER_03]: Like someone just said, we're a city full of talented, bright, motivated people that have great ideas and it just seems like no one's talking.

420
00:44:23,681 --> 00:44:30,403
[SPEAKER_03]: I'm open to any advice on how we as residents can support some progress.

421
00:44:32,885 --> 00:44:35,286
[SPEAKER_07]: I mean, at this point, the budget is with the mayor.

422
00:44:35,346 --> 00:44:37,346
[SPEAKER_07]: The mayor and her administration write the budget.

423
00:44:37,907 --> 00:44:44,569
[SPEAKER_07]: Unfortunately, it's like a 90% baked cake by the time it gets to us and we can only do so much.

424
00:44:45,269 --> 00:44:48,290
[SPEAKER_07]: So I think at this point, it's reaching out to the administration.

425
00:44:48,550 --> 00:44:57,353
[SPEAKER_07]: When it gets to the council, we will absolutely do our best, but it's the mayor, the bulk of the work is with her and her administration.

426
00:44:59,072 --> 00:44:59,793
[SPEAKER_05]: I can't thank you.

427
00:45:00,153 --> 00:45:01,474
[SPEAKER_05]: Thank you for the residents speaking.

428
00:45:01,514 --> 00:45:12,280
[SPEAKER_05]: I think that I think first, I think that I appreciate that we have residents like our present company that's reaching out and saying, how can we help?

429
00:45:12,340 --> 00:45:13,741
[SPEAKER_05]: And that's what's impressive about method.

430
00:45:13,781 --> 00:45:14,762
[SPEAKER_05]: That's what makes method great.

431
00:45:14,782 --> 00:45:18,024
[SPEAKER_05]: I think that's what is keeping method above ground right now.

432
00:45:18,124 --> 00:45:25,909
[SPEAKER_05]: I mean, and not going underwater completely, but I know it's not anger.

433
00:45:26,510 --> 00:45:26,951
[SPEAKER_05]: it's frustrating.

434
00:45:26,971 --> 00:45:27,653
[SPEAKER_05]: Because it isn't.

435
00:45:27,713 --> 00:45:28,835
[SPEAKER_05]: It's really frustration.

436
00:45:29,456 --> 00:45:32,543
[SPEAKER_05]: And the frustration is if you if you look at

437
00:45:36,952 --> 00:45:56,346
[SPEAKER_05]: Next week, our neighbor community on Wednesday is the mayor is already meeting with their city council, and they've already the city council and neighbor community has already been given total autonomy what the budget looks like and where, where money is going on a day to day basis so at least they have an understanding where it's going.

438
00:45:56,927 --> 00:45:58,888
[SPEAKER_05]: You have the school committee on that same.

439
00:46:01,209 --> 00:46:27,571
[SPEAKER_05]: The same side has already been talking with the mayor and the council about what Council saying was talking about is sustainability for what was spent with so money and coven money and seeing what are what are programs that could be sustained in their budget, and then looking at a long term plan to make sure those very important pieces that have shown through data that it's needed in the community and how they can fund it.

440
00:46:28,547 --> 00:46:36,910
[SPEAKER_05]: I think what you're seeing here is the frustration that we don't even see, we don't see that tunnel, let alone the light in the tunnel.

441
00:46:37,710 --> 00:46:54,615
[SPEAKER_05]: So we're gonna be, and there was a circus, the last budget season was a circus, but I think it became a circus because this council would not accept to walk away without the basic needs that we need to be successful.

442
00:46:55,663 --> 00:47:05,593
[SPEAKER_05]: And, again, I appreciate the member of the community, I think that Council President mentioned answered that perfectly I think it's asking the administration.

443
00:47:07,423 --> 00:47:08,624
[SPEAKER_05]: you know, where is the process?

444
00:47:08,704 --> 00:47:08,944
[SPEAKER_05]: Why?

445
00:47:09,564 --> 00:47:14,208
[SPEAKER_05]: Why hasn't there been transparency that and I think that's what the mayor has run on.

446
00:47:14,228 --> 00:47:17,830
[SPEAKER_05]: You know, she ran on that a few years back as transparency.

447
00:47:17,850 --> 00:47:22,213
[SPEAKER_05]: And I, you know, I was so excited because I sat next to her.

448
00:47:22,673 --> 00:47:28,918
[SPEAKER_05]: And we talked about the issues and, you know, how appalled she was that we would get the budget

449
00:47:30,035 --> 00:47:34,204
[SPEAKER_05]: weeks two weeks before, and we didn't even see a budget last year.

450
00:47:34,565 --> 00:47:35,888
[SPEAKER_05]: And right now we don't even snip.

451
00:47:36,329 --> 00:47:39,857
[SPEAKER_05]: We don't even see a financial to show us what our financial climate is.

452
00:47:40,298 --> 00:47:40,418
[SPEAKER_05]: So

453
00:47:42,145 --> 00:48:01,751
[SPEAKER_05]: It's frustrating and it makes me very nervous that the fact that, you know, we have kids in the public schools and we don't know what what what to tell them we have parents that are asking me, you know, the rumors out there about cuts and and layoffs and if that's the case, should they be looking to maybe go to a private school or move to a parochial school.

454
00:48:02,132 --> 00:48:05,993
[SPEAKER_05]: And to me that that's the problem with this community, this administration that

455
00:48:06,573 --> 00:48:13,716
[SPEAKER_05]: you're you're leaving things so open ended that you're driving people to make decisions that they truly can't afford.

456
00:48:14,516 --> 00:48:23,699
[SPEAKER_05]: And again, I appreciate you looking out and appreciate the involvement and but let's reach out to the mayor.

457
00:48:23,739 --> 00:48:27,501
[SPEAKER_05]: I mean, again, this is furthest from a political ploy.

458
00:48:27,541 --> 00:48:30,302
[SPEAKER_05]: This is something that we've been talking about for years.

459
00:48:30,522 --> 00:48:31,462
[SPEAKER_05]: This is something new.

460
00:48:31,562 --> 00:48:33,023
[SPEAKER_05]: So thank you so much.

461
00:48:34,937 --> 00:48:35,197
[SPEAKER_07]: Thank you.

462
00:48:35,237 --> 00:48:39,460
[SPEAKER_07]: Any further discussion from the vice president bears?

463
00:48:39,841 --> 00:48:40,581
[SPEAKER_02]: Thank you, Madam President.

